05277nam a22006615i 9780822388395DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20062006ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223883957 a10.1515/97808223883952doi  a(DE-B1597)553985  a(OCoLC)1148127820  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aE184.M5bM465 2006 7aBIO0060002bisacsh1 aMéndez-Negrete, Josie, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aLas hijas de Juan :bDaughters Betrayed /cJosie Méndez-Negrete; ed. by Walter D. Mignolo, Irene Silverblatt, Sonia Saldívar-Hull. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2006] 4c©2006  a1 online resource (224 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aLatin America otherwise : languages, empires, nations : 4600tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAbout the Series -- tAcknowledgments -- tAuthor’s Note -- tPrologue: Sin padre -- tMéxico lindo y querido. Dearest and beloved Mexico -- t¿A donde iran los muertos? Quién sabe a donde iran. Where will the dead go? Who knows where they will go -- tBuscando abrigo y no lo encontraran. Searching for shelter they will never find -- tQue lejos estoy del suelo donde he nacido. So far from the land that gave me birth -- tShe kept her head in a jar by the door. Mantuvo su cabeza en el jarrón junto a la puerta -- tEpilogue: Purging the Skeletons, Bone by Bone -- tSongs Quoted in Text -- tGlossary0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aLas hijas de Juan shatters the silence surrounding experiences of incest within a working-class Mexican American family. Both a feminist memoir and a hopeful meditation on healing, it is Josie Méndez-Negrete’s story of how she and her siblings and mother survived years of violence and sexual abuse at the hands of her father.Méndez-Negrete was born in Mexico, in the state of Zacatecas. She recalls a joyous childhood growing up in the midst of Tabasco, a vibrant town filled with extended family. Her father, though, had dreams of acquiring wealth in el norte. He worked sun-up to sun-down in the fields of south Texas. Returning home to Mexico, his pockets full of dollars, he spent evenings drinking and womanizing.When Méndez-Negrete was eleven, her father moved the family to the United States, where they eventually settled in California’s Santa Clara Valley. There her father began molesting his daughters, viciously beating them and their mother. Within the impoverished immigrant family, the abuse continued for years, until a family friend brought it to the attention of child welfare authorities. Méndez-Negrete’s father was tried, convicted, and imprisoned.Las hijas de Juan is told chronologically, from the time Méndez-Negrete was a child until she was a young adult trying, along with the rest of her family, to come to terms with her father’s brutal legacy. It is a harrowing story of abuse and shame compounded by cultural and linguistic isolation and a system of patriarchy that devalues the experiences of women and girls. At the same time, Las hijas de Juan is an inspiring tale, filled with strong women and hard-won solace found in traditional Mexican cooking, songs, and storytelling.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aChild sexual abusevCase studies. 0aFamily violencevCase studies. 0aIncest victimszUnited StatesvBiography. 0aMexican American families. 0aMexican American womenvBiography. 0aMexican American womenxSocial conditions. 0aMexican AmericansvBiography. 0aMigrant agricultural laborerszUnited StatesvBiography. 0aWomen's rightsvCase studies. 7aBIOGRAPHY & AUTOBIOGRAPHY / Historical.2bisacsh1 aMignolo, Walter D., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aSaldívar-Hull, Sonia, eeditor.4edt4http://id.